                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d732">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890E.01/147: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gwynn</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="50" xml:id="d732fn50">Repeated to the Ambassador in the United Kingdom
                        as No. 4017, August 24, 10 p.m.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-08-23T19:00:00+02:00"
                            >August 23, 1942—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 24—9:07 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>300. In paragraph 9 of my 289, August 16, I said “it might lead to conflict et
                    cetera”. I put it that way as I was anxious not to go beyond de Gaulle’s thought
                    though I suspected he really meant armed conflict. He having repeated the same
                    thing today I asked him to explain frankly what his statement implied. He said
                    clearly, that if Churchill refused to cede in this matter he would request the
                    British to leave this territory and if they refused to leave he would take
                    measures to force them out.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Cairo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gwynn</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
